Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a
large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, @Italian Seasoning{1/2%tsp}, @salt{},
and @pepper{}. (You'll use more Italian Seasoning later.)

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, trim and cut @zucchini{1} crosswise into ¼-inch-thick
rounds. Quarter @lemon{1}. Halve @ciabatta bread{2}. Finely chop @sun-dried tomatoes{1.5%ounce}.

Toss zucchini in a #medium bowl{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon},
half the @garlic powder{1/2%teaspoon}, @Italian Seasoning{1/2%tsp}, @salt{}, and
@pepper{}. (Use the remaining Italian Seasoning as you like.)

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add zucchini in a
single layer; cook until golden brown and just tender, ~{2-4%minutes} per side.
Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @pesto{4%tablespoon},
and a squeeze of @lemon juice{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread a layer of pesto mayo onto cut sides of ciabattas.

Fill ciabattas with @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup}, sun-dried tomatoes, and a few
slices of zucchini. (You may have some left over—feel free to serve on the side,
if you like.)

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for zucchini over medium heat. Once hot, add
sandwiches; press down with a #spatula{}. Cook, pressing occasionally, until
bread is toasted and cheese melts, ~{2-4%minutes} per side. (For 4 servings,
cook in batches if needed.) TIP: If pan seems dry when flipping sandwiches, add
another drizzle of oil or ½ TBSP butter. Lower heat if bread browns too quickly.

Transfer panini to a #cutting board{}. Once cool enough to handle, halve on a
diagonal.

Divide panini between plates and serve with potato wedges on the side.